default&#xa0;default2. Introduction of the work of Quality of Life Associationdefault&#xa0;
default2.1 To answer the need
defaults
default of unexploded ordnance  victims, and people with disabilities  the Quality of Life Association  
defaultwas 
default set up in 2011 and became the first Lao Civil Society Organisation  providing assistance and support services to victims of unexploded ordnance , people with disabilities  and poor families in the Xieng Khouang Province in Lao PDR.  The QLA Operational Team and Board of Directors are made up of Lao nationals, some of whom are UXO survivors. The objective to 
defaultset up the association in Xieng Khuang province because it is one of the most bomb affected areas in Laos. “Xieng Khuang, know for the Plain of Jars, is also the plain of scars.”
default&#xa0;
default2.2 The presence of the buried bombs affects the quality of life of local people in many ways. Economic development is stalled. Children need to learn at an early age that they must be careful around their homes and villages. Agriculture is more difficult and often dangerous. Many people who have survived an accident need expensive medical care and follow-up treatment; families who have lost a loved one also need economic support and new livelihoods.             
default2.3 The QLA supports UXO affected communities and PWD through training on animal raising, weaving and dyeing, and the production of hand-crafted souvenirs. Another important aspect is emergency and long term medical care, including rehabilitation, as well as psycho-social support.
default  
defaultThe QLA has run training courses for UXO accident survivors, family members of UXO victims and PWD in nine villages of the province
default. The Association
default  targeted 
defaultthese villages 
default for assistance after it conducted a survey among local communities.
default“We select 15 people representing 15 families in a village to attend a course. We firstly give priority to a UXO affected family member and UXO survivors and persons with disability because they are our target groups. Our second priority is poor families. After attending a training course on livestock or poultry raising, each person is given 600,000-700,000 kip to use as capital to undertake this activity. Those who attend a training course on weaving, making handicrafts or tailoring can sell their products at the QLA village shop.” 
default   
defaultThe association provides all the materials needed for trainees to make the products and pays them for each item in accordance with their ability and the orders placed by the QLA. A training course on tailoring has taught women how to sew small fabric bags to contain laptops and mobile phones.
default 
defaultThe association will continue to help UXO affected communities and PWD in all districts of the province because a large number of people need assistance and have no permanent job
default 
defaultto provide them with a regular source of income.                                                                      
